ss with authorization2star  aSince the fall of the Iron Curtain, formerly socialist countries have gone through manifold transformations, whilst remnants of socialism remain ubiquitous. The volume explores various spaces of the postsocialist landscape, presenting a mixture of real and imaginary spaces, of memory and nostalgia, of aesthetical and political symbolism, of the global East and the global South, of academic and essayistic writing. It casts a glance at the heterogeneous relics of socialism and their transformation in very different parts of the world. From the description of (post-)socialist interiors, façades, neighborhoods, parks, monuments, and objects towards the imaginary spaces of literature, the contributors describe the concreteness and intimacy of some of the places that span across and even beyond of what is left of the »second world« today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCultural landscapeszFormer communist countries. 4aCultural Studies. 4aEast European Studies. 4aHybrid Spatialities. 4aLiterature. 4aMemory Culture. 4aSociety. 4aSpace. 4aUrban Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aEast European Studies.  aHybrid Spatialities.  aLiterature.  aMemory Culture.  aSociety.  aSpace.  aUrban Studies.1 aBeganović, Davor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDitchev, Ivaylo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrews-Sylla, Gesine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgemberdieva, Gulzat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrank, Susi K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoleva, Daniela, eco